('Adolescent Career Development Center', '', '565 Gerard Avenue', '2nd Floor', 'Bronx', 'NY', '10456', '(718) 742-6181', '', '', '', '(718) 583-6090', '', '', '', 'The mission of the Adolescent Career Development Center is to assist adolescents with histories of emotional and behavioral problems to achieve independence in adulthood. We believe that one of the most important keys to their success lies in their ability to obtain meaningful work.\n\nThe primary activities of this program are designed to expose emotionally disturbed youth to a variety of academic and vocational experiences including world of work internships, to equip them with the appropriate knowledge, understanding, and preparation to enter the workforce.\n\nThe Center is located at Bronx Children''s Psychiatric Center, and provides services to adolescents in Bronx Children''s Psychiatric Center''s hospital and community-based programs operated through collaboration with public and private mental health organizations, the business community and local schools and community organizations.', 'Mental Health', 'Child and Adolescent Services', '', '', 10, -73.9289932, 40.8195992, '8', '200'),
('Adolescent Skills Center', '', '369 East 148th St', '', 'Bronx', 'NY', '10455', '(718) 292-7880 ext. 208 or 213', '', '', '', '(718) 292-7950', '', '', '', 'The Bronx Adolescent Skills Centers help emotionally disturbed adolescents who have often had a very tough time in school, suffer with low self-esteem and have few, if any, job skills by offering an array of vocational, educational, experimental, career planning and job placement services that empowers adolescents for the world of work.\n\nThe Adolescent Skills Centers prepare adolescents with histories of emotional and behavioral problems to achieve independence in adulthood. We believe that one of the most important keys to this success is their ability to obtain meaningful and productive work.\n\nOur programs offer a menu of vocationally-oriented services which include: vocational skills assessment, GED and literacy classes, computer instruction, exposure to a variety of diverse job experiences in real work settings, internship placements in competitive businesses, job coaching, peer support and case management services.\n\nUnderstanding that family members and caregivers play an important role in shaping adolescents'' vocational development, parents are involved in the initial orientation sessions and through the period of time that their children are participants in the program.', 'Mental Health', 'Child and Adolescent Services', '', '', 11, -73.9190674, 40.8156586, '8', '200'),
